  "prompt": "Do Go-Back-N ARQ and Selective Repeat ARQ use cumulative acknowledgements or an acknowledgement for every individual packet?",
  "response": "Go-Back-N ARQ and Selective Repeat ARQ have different approaches to acknowledgements.\n\n### Go-Back-N ARQ:\n- **Cumulative Acknowledgements:** Go-Back-N ARQ uses cumulative acknowledgements. This means that when a receiver sends an acknowledgment (ACK), it indicates that it has successfully received all packets up to a certain sequence number. For example, if the receiver acknowledges packet 5, it means that packets 1, 2, 3, 4, and 5 have been successfully received. If a packet is lost or corrupted, the sender must go back and retransmit that packet and all subsequent packets.\n\n### Selective Repeat ARQ:\n- **Individual Acknowledgements:** Selective Repeat ARQ uses individual acknowledgements for each packet. Each packet is acknowledged separately, so if a packet is received correctly but one is lost, the receiver can send an ACK for the packets that have been successfully received, while indicating which specific packet needs to be retransmitted. This allows for more efficient use of the network, as only the lost packets are retransmitted, not all subsequent packets.\n\nIn summary, Go-Back-N ARQ uses cumulative acknowledgements, whereas Selective Repeat ARQ uses individual acknowledgements for each packet.",
